<DocPage eyebrow="UNITY / TESTING" title="Testing UI" lead="Gua.Testing.Unity starts Unity Editor Play Mode or a Windows Mono Player and connects the shared IGuaContext to its bridge." description="External Unity UI testing with Gua.Testing.Unity." section="unity">
  <h2>1. Add test packages</h2><p><code>Gua.Testing.Unity</code> is not published to NuGet yet. Reference its source project during the branch preview; after publication, keep Core, Testing, and Testing.Unity on the same release version.</p><CodeBlock title="Preview ProjectReference" lang="xml" code={`<ProjectReference Include="../gua/bindings/dotnet/src/Gua.Testing.Unity/Gua.Testing.Unity.csproj" />`} />
  <h2>2. Start a Player or Editor</h2><CodeBlock title="Build and test a rendered Player" lang="csharp" code={`using Gua.Core;
using Gua.Testing;
using Gua.Testing.Unity;

var player = UnityPlayerBuilder.Build(@"game/Assets/Scenes/Title.unity");
using var host = UnitySceneTestHost.LoadRenderedPlayer(
    player, UnitySceneTestHostOptions.StrictIsolation);
var start = host.Context.FindNodeByRole("button", "Start Game");
host.Context.EnqueueClick(start);
var screenshot = host.CaptureScreenshot();`} />
  <div class="table-wrap"><table><thead><tr><th>Entry point</th><th>Use</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>LoadPlayer</code></td><td>Existing <code>-batchmode -nographics</code> Player for fast semantic tests</td></tr><tr><td><code>LoadRenderedPlayer</code></td><td>Rendered existing Player for screenshots and visual tests</td></tr><tr><td><code>LoadEditor</code></td><td>Open a scene in Editor Play Mode</td></tr><tr><td><code>BuildAndLoadPlayer</code></td><td>Build and start a Windows x64 Mono Player</td></tr></tbody></table></div>
  <h2>Parallel isolation</h2><p><code>UseAvailableBridgePort</code> defaults to <code>true</code>. The host selects a loopback port and passes it as <code>GUA_BRIDGE_PORT</code>, avoiding a fixed collision on port 8765. It closes the listener before Unity binds, so a small selection-to-bind race remains under extreme concurrency.</p>
  <CodeBlock title="Explicit options" lang="csharp" code={`var options = new UnitySceneTestHostOptions {
    UnityExecutablePath = @"C:/Program Files/Unity/Hub/Editor/6000.5.3f1/Editor/Unity.exe",
    ProjectPath = @"C:/src/game",
    UseAvailableBridgePort = true,
    TeardownResetPolicy = GuaResetPolicy.Strict,
    CaptureDiagnosticsBeforeTeardown = true,
};`} />
  <Callout kind="warn" title="Editor project lock"><p><code>LoadEditor</code> checks <code>Temp/UnityLockfile</code>. If another Editor owns the project, it fails with the command and lock path instead of waiting ambiguously.</p></Callout>
  <h2>Diagnostics</h2><p><code>CreateDiagnosticsSession()</code> adds the single <code>-logFile</code> Unity log, PID, bridge URL, and log path to shared artifacts. stdout and stderr are not redirected separately. Strict teardown reports leaked requests or events instead of deleting them silently. <code>SceneTimeout</code> currently serves mainly as the default screenshot timeout; it does not wait for scene transitions automatically.</p>
  <Callout kind="tip" title="Unity.exe resolution"><p>The host checks <code>UnityExecutablePath</code>, then <code>UNITY_EXECUTABLE</code>, then the newest install below <code>C:\Program Files\Unity\Hub\Editor</code>.</p></Callout>
</DocPage>
